7 action items; 0 were resolved in Epic 0.5. Epic 4 had 9 action items; 0 were resolved in Epic 5. The retrospective process generates action items that are never executed. This is a process failure, not a documentation gap. Either reduce the number of action items to only those that will actually be done in the next epic, or wire action items into sprint-planning as mandatory stories.\n\n- **Story 6-1 was harder than expected because of NFR9 interaction.** The 300-line limit forced a 3-file split with an `ink-app.tsx` indirection layer to avoid circular imports. The split itself was architecturally sound, but it was not anticipated during story creation — the story listed 5 files to modify, not 3 new files to create. Stories that rewrite existing code near the line limit should flag NFR9 risk explicitly.\n\n- **Story 6-2 was harder than expected because `makeLineHandler` was untestable.** The production line handler was a closure inside `run.ts`, impossible to import. The test initially reimplemented it — a pattern the code review correctly flagged as HIGH severity. The fix (extracting `createLineProcessor`) was the right call but changed the scope of the story from \"add a test\" to \"refactor production code + add a test.\" Stories targeting integration tests should audit whether the code under test is actually importable before scoping.\n\n- **Immediate attention:** Fix cost accumulation data loss bug (events before `sprintInfo` init are silently dropped). This affects the accuracy of the cost display for every `codeharness run` session.\n\n- **Backlog:** Automate stale Docker container cleanup before verification runs. Infrastructure friction consumed manual time in every verification phase across both stories.\n\n- **Process improvement to encode in tooling:** Wire retrospective action items into sprint-planning as candidate stories. Currently, action items are written to markdown and forgotten. The sprint-planning workflow should read the previous retro's act